				</div><div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/24/blogs/reading-with/reading-with-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/24/blogs/reading-with/reading-with-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/24/blogs/reading-with/reading-with-articleInline.jpg" id="100000003417047" width="190" height="271" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="271"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Ayad Akhtar is a playwright, novelist and screenwriter. His play &#8220;Disgraced&#8221; won the Pulitzer Prize; his latest play, &#8220;The Invisible Hand&#8221; &#8212; about global finance and Pakistani militancy &#8212; is currently running at New York Theater Workshop.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He says The Times is the home page on his computer, so he dips into the paper several times a day. A few days a week, Mr. Akhtar says, he reads the paper in print.</em></p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Do you read differently when you read the printed paper?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Reading the paper that way is both more satisfying and filled with greater surprises. My eye wanders in a way that it doesn&#8217;t online. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Reading it this morning in print was a case in point. I started with the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/24/business/media/sonys-the-interview-will-come-to-some-theaters-after-all.html">Sony article</a>, which led me to the Business section, where I got distracted by the piece on <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/24/business/international/plastic-surgery-tourism-brings-chinese-to-south-korea.html">cosmetic surgery in South Korea</a>, which then led deeper into the Business pages where <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/12/23/success-and-failure-in-a-year-of-prominent-deals/">Steven Davidoff Solomon&#8217;s assessment</a> of the year&#8217;s major deals delighted me.<br />
 <span id="more-8093"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I turned a couple pages as I sipped at coffee and found myself saddened and captivated and was outraged by the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/24/sports/ncaafootball/transcript-of-jameis-winston-hearing-reveals-accusers-words-and-florida-states-complicity.html">piece</a> in Sports Wednesday on the handling of rape allegations at Florida State University.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Then back to the front page, where the &#8220;choose your own adventure&#8221; began all over again.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Do you find ideas for your work in the paper? </p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Absolutely. Almost daily. I think part of me reads it with that in mind. And often the connection isn&#8217;t obvious. I may be reading a story about something that jogs an idea about another seemingly unrelated thing. Today&#8217;s piece in Food <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/24/dining/danny-bowien-reopens-mission-chinese-food.html">about Danny Bowien</a> was like that. Reading the paper is part of what it means, to me, to be engaged with the world. </p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What&#8217;s the scariest thing you read in today&#8217;s paper?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/24/business/international/plastic-surgery-tourism-brings-chinese-to-south-korea.html">article</a> about the craze for cosmetic surgery in South Korea. Wow. Don&#8217;t know what else to say about it. The number of people wanting to get their jaws broken to look better is truly mind-boggling. </p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Any particular thoughts about Sonyâs new plans to release &#8220;The Interview&#8221;? </p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Itâs probably not a surprise that I think releasing the movie in some form is necessary. And a positive development. The irony, though, is that we&#8217;re talking about a film poking macabre fun at a subject about which there is absolutely no controversy in our body politic.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This is less a matter of freedom of expression than freedom within the marketplace. Which I don&#8217;t see as the same thing.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Anything in today&#8217;s Arts section of special interest? </p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Dwight Garner&#8217;s <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/24/books/here-richard-mcguires-new-graphic-novel.html">review</a> of the graphic novel &#8220;Here.&#8221; I put it on the list for my next trip to the bookstore.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A.O. Scott&#8217;s <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/24/movies/two-days-one-night-from-jean-pierre-and-luc-dardenne.html ">remarkable assessment of Marion Cotillard</a> in the new Dardenne brothers film: &#8220;Her shoulders slumped, her eyes weary, her gait heavy, Ms. Cotillard moves past naturalism into something impossible to doubt and hard to describe.&#8221; I read that sentence and a chill went down my back.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And the bemused discovery, in Arts, Briefly, that there would be a <a href="//artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/12/22/freud-gets-marathon-reading-treatment/">complete reading</a> of Freud&#8217;s âCivilization and Its Discontentsâ on Jan. 3 at Judson Memorial Church.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As someone whose work has been reviewed positively in The Times, can you speak to the experience of being reviewed? </p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Other than to say that it&#8217;s an honor to have the opportunity to be reviewed at all, I&#8217;d only say this: One waits with bated breath &#8212; in equal parts terror and excitement &#8212; for the moment that review posts online!</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Anything you think should be but isnât covered in the Arts section? </p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I think the section is remarkable. I mean, really. I have discovered so many new voices because of it. In particular, I find the theater coverage truly astonishing.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It might seem a little unbefitting of me to say that, as it&#8217;s obviously the business I&#8217;m in. But there really is an exhaustiveness to The Times&#8217;s coverage of the theater. So many productions and artists end up getting thoughtful ink. Reviews of London shows and Off Off Broadway shows. Every production on Broadway, and virtually every production at an Off Broadway theater. I mean, I can&#8217;t think of anything comparable in any paper anywhere.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Do you read the editorials? Do they ever change your mind? </p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I do read the editorials. Perhaps it&#8217;s the artist&#8217;s long habit of seeking to understand and empathize, but I often find that I am more interested in finding ways to identify with an argument rather than discovering whether I agree with it or not. It&#8217;s always struck me that the world comprises so many opposing points of view, almost all of which are in some way right. And that the real drama of the world is in fact just that: the constant battle of points of view, all of which are experienced &#8212; by those who espouse them &#8212; as justified. </p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Are there columnists whom you especially like to read or with whom you like to disagree? </p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I&#8217;m always interested in what&#8217;s on David Brooks&#8217;s mind. I enjoy his thought-provoking attempts to search beneath the ever-shifting tide of current events. And I appreciate his persistent attempt to speak intelligently about ethics in a wider social and psychological context. </p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What piece in today&#8217;s paper are you most likely to talk about with friends or colleagues? </p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Reforesting. Without a doubt.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/24/science/earth/restored-forests-are-making-inroads-against-climate-change-.html">front-page story</a>  on restored forests captivated me and got my imagination going. I&#8217;m currently working on a new story having to do with the effects of globalization, and that story really excited me. It can seem rare to find a story about the big picture that is as encouraging as that. </p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On the front page <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/24/world/cubas-zeal-for-tight-control-clashes-with-need-for-growth.html">we find RaÃºl Castro</a> describing a new container terminal as &#8220;a transcendent project for the national economy.&#8221;  A transcendent economic project. Does the idea amuse you? </p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The political rhetoric of economic discourse is a subject unto itself. I remember reading about Newt Gingrich&#8217;s vocabulary lessons on language as the key to power in George Packer&#8217;s &#8220;The Unwinding&#8221; (which I picked up following a wonderful <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/05/29/books/the-unwinding-by-george-packer.html?pagewanted=all">review</a> in Books of the Times). Mr. Gingrich discovered that discussing one&#8217;s opponents with words like &#8220;betray, bizarre, bosses, bureaucracy, cheat, corrupt, crisis, liberal, lie, limit, radical, shame, status quo, taxes, they/them, waste, welfare&#8221; put them on the defensive. Describing one&#8217;s own side with words like &#8220;change, children, choice/choose, common sense, crusade, drama, empower, family, lead, liberty, light, pride, reform, tough, truth, vision, we/us/our&#8221; ensured that you&#8217;d already won the argument. I think you could add the word &#8220;transcendent&#8221; to that second list. </p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Iâm betting you have been following events since Ferguson and wonder what you make of the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/25/us/berkeley-missouri-police-shooting.html">latest developments</a>.   </p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I&#8217;m from Milwaukee, a place I still keep close tabs on. My folks live there, and I love my hometown a great deal. It also happens to be the most segregated city in America, and the recent development with another police officer not facing charges after pouring 14 bullets into an unarmed man after he had gotten hold of the officer&#8217;s baton is, well, disheartening to say the least. The terrible killings of the officers in Brooklyn this weekend, the Eric Garner decision, Ferguson &#8212; all of it speaks to a profound crisis in our country, a sense of being pitted against each other as Americans, the modes of us and them becoming increasingly our way of understanding ourselves as citizens.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Anything that made you laugh? </p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/24/upshot/trending-holiday-gift-searches.html">most-Googled-Christmas-gift lists</a> on B4 in Business. That the most searched gift in Chicago, Miami, Phoenix and Seattle was &#8220;Cards Against Humanity.&#8221; Had no idea what that was. Googled it myself. Looks like I might want to get those, too, now. </p>
	</div>
